The line passing through $\begin{pmatrix}2 \\1 \end{pmatrix}$ with direction $\begin{pmatrix}2 \\1 \end{pmatrix}$ can be parameterized as
\begin{align*}
x&= 2s +2,\\
y& = s+1.
\end{align*}
Now, we need to find the intersection point between this line and the original line. The original line is 
\begin{align*}
x&= 4t + 2,\\
y& = t+2.
\end{align*} Setting these two lines equal to each other, we obtain a system of two equations with two unknowns, $t$ and $s$. The first equations $x = 4t+2$ and $x = 2s+2$ give us
\begin{align*}
4t+2&= 2s+2 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad 4t&=2s 
\end{align*}
The second equations $y = t+2$ and $y = s+1$ give us
\begin{align*}
t+2&= s+1 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad t&= s-1.
\end{align*}
We can substitute this expression for $t$ into $4t = 2s$ to get
\begin{align*}
4(s-1) &= 2s \\
\Rightarrow\qquad 4s-4 &= 2s \\
\Rightarrow\qquad 2s&= 4 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad s &= 2.
\end{align*}
Now we can substitute this value for $s$ back into the second equation $t = s - 1$ to get
\begin{align*}
t &= 2 -1 \\
\Rightarrow\qquad t &= 1.
\end{align*}
We now have the point of intersection: (<|reserved_special_token_243|>(4*1+2),(1+2)) = (6,3)>
